Images and Attributes

## HTML Attributes

### What are Attributes?

**Attributes** provide additional information about an HTML element. They are written inside the **opening tag** and help define the element's behavior or properties.

### Example

```html
<img src="cat.jpg" alt="A cute cat" width="300" height="200" />
```

### Common Image Attributes

| Attribute | Purpose                                                                                                            |
| --------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `src`     | Specifies the path (source) of the image.                                                                          |
| `alt`     | Provides alternative text describing the image. It is displayed if the image cannot load and helps screen readers. |
| `width`   | Specifies the width of the image.                                                                                  |
| `height`  | Specifies the height of the image.                                                                                 |

### Key Points

- Attributes are always written in the **opening tag**.
- They are written as **name="value"** pairs.
- One HTML element can have multiple attributes.

**Syntax:**

```html
<element attribute="value">Content</element>
```

## HTML Links

HTML uses the **`<a>` (anchor)** element to create hyperlinks.

### Types of Links

#### 1. Internal Links

Links that point to **other pages within the same website**.

**Example:**

```html
<a href="about.html">About Us</a>
```

---

#### 2. External Links

Links that point to **pages on another website**.

**Example:**

```html
<a href="https://www.google.com">Google</a>
```

---

## Opening a Link in a New Tab

To open a link in a **new browser tab**, use the `target` attribute with the value `_blank`.

**Example:**

```html
<a href="https://www.google.com" target="_blank">Visit Google</a>
```

---

## Common Link Attributes

| Attribute | Purpose                                      |
| --------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| `href`    | Specifies the destination URL or webpage.    |
| `target`  | Specifies where the linked page should open. |

### Common `target` Values

| Value    | Description                               |
| -------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `_self`  | Opens the link in the same tab (default). |
| `_blank` | Opens the link in a new tab.              |

---

## Syntax

```html
<a href="URL" target="_blank">Link Text</a>
```

---

## Key Points

- `<a>` is used to create hyperlinks.
- `href` specifies the destination of the link.
- `target="_blank"` opens the link in a new tab.
- Use **internal links** to navigate within your website.
- Use **external links** to navigate to other websites.

## Structuring a Web Page

HTML provides **semantic elements** to organize the structure of a webpage. These elements make your code easier to read and improve accessibility and SEO.

### Common Structural Elements

| Element     | Purpose                                                                                                                      |
| ----------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `<header>`  | Represents the top section of a webpage or a section. It usually contains the logo, heading, or navigation.                  |
| `<nav>`     | Contains the navigation links (menus) used to move between pages or sections.                                                |
| `<article>` | Represents independent, self-contained content such as a blog post, news article, or forum post.                             |
| `<footer>`  | Represents the bottom section of a webpage. It usually contains copyright information, contact details, or additional links. |

### Basic Page Structure

```html
<header>
  <h1>My Website</h1>
</header>

<nav>
  <a href="#">Home</a>
  <a href="#">About</a>
  <a href="#">Contact</a>
</nav>

<article>
  <h2>Article Title</h2>
  <p>This is the main content of the article.</p>
</article>

<footer>
  <p>&copy; 2026 My Website</p>
</footer>
```

---

## HTML Entities

**HTML Entities** are special codes used to display reserved characters or symbols that cannot be typed directly in HTML.

### Example

| Entity   | Output | Purpose                        |
| -------- | ------ | ------------------------------ |
| `&copy;` | ©      | Displays the copyright symbol. |

**Example:**

```html
<p>&copy; 2026 My Website. All Rights Reserved.</p>
```

**Output:**

> © 2026 My Website. All Rights Reserved.

---

## Key Points

- Use semantic elements to create a well-structured webpage.
- `<header>` defines the top section.
- `<nav>` contains navigation links.
- `<article>` contains independent content.
- `<footer>` defines the bottom section of the page.
- HTML entities are used to display special characters, such as `&copy;` for **©**.

## Semantic HTML

### What is Semantic HTML?

**Semantic HTML** means using HTML elements that clearly describe the purpose and meaning of the content they contain.

Instead of using generic elements like `<div>` and `<span>` everywhere, semantic elements make the structure of a webpage easier to understand for browsers, search engines, and developers.

### Examples of Semantic Elements

| Element     | Purpose                                                              |
| ----------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `<header>`  | Defines the header of a webpage or section.                          |
| `<nav>`     | Contains navigation links.                                           |
| `<main>`    | Contains the main content of the webpage.                            |
| `<section>` | Groups related content together.                                     |
| `<article>` | Represents independent content, such as a blog post or news article. |
| `<aside>`   | Contains related or sidebar content.                                 |
| `<footer>`  | Defines the footer of a webpage or section.                          |
| `<strong>`  | Indicates important text.                                            |
| `<em>`      | Indicates emphasized text.                                           |

### Benefits of Semantic HTML

- Makes HTML code easier to read and understand.
- Improves accessibility for screen readers.
- Helps search engines better understand the content (SEO).
- Makes websites easier to maintain.

### Key Point

> **Semantic HTML is the practice of using HTML elements that clearly describe the meaning and purpose of the content they contain.**
